ship Perspectives on the High Frequency of Divorce among Uyghurs in Southern Xinjiang, China -- t9. The Ends of Divorce: Marital Dispute as a Locus of Social Change in India -- tConclusion: Islamic Divorce in Context and in Action: Notes from the Field -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIslamic Divorce in the 21st Century shows the wide range of Muslim experiences in marital disputes and in seeking Islamic divorces. For Muslims, having the ability to divorce in accordance with Islamic law is of paramount importance. However, Muslim experiences of divorce practice differ tremendously. The chapters in this volume discuss Islamic divorce from West Africa to Southeast Asia, and each story explores aspects of the everyday realities of disputing and divorcing Muslim couples face in the twenty-first century. The book’s cross-cultural and comparative look at Islamic divorce indicates that Muslim divorces are impacted by global religious discourses on Islamic authority, authenticity, and gender; by global patterns of and approaches to secularity; and by global economic inequalities and attendant patterns of urbanization and migration. Studying divorce as a mode of Islamic law in practice shows us that the Islamic legal tradition is flexible, malleable, and context-dependent.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aDivorce (Islamic law) 0aDivorce (Islamic law). 0aDivorcexReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aHusband and wife (Islamic law) 0aHusband and wife (Islamic law). 0aMarriagexReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aSeparation (Islamic law) 0aSeparation (Islamic law). 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aIslamic divorce, Islamic family dynamics, divorce law, Islamic law, law interpretation, Islamic marriage, South Asian law, w